<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ901221-0137</DOCNO><DOCID>901221-0137.</DOCID><HL>   GE's Internal Query Probes   Alleged Israeli Kickbacks</HL><DATE>12/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7</SO><CO>   GE MDEST</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   FAIRFIELD, Conn. -- General Electric Co. said it isconducting an internal company investigation in connectionwith an alleged kickback scheme involving Israeli purchasesof U.S. weapons.   As reported in the Washington Post yesterday, police inIsrael are investigating the Israeli air force procurement ofmilitary equipment from U.S. contractors. The allegations arethat millions of dollars in kickbacks were siphoned off tosenior Israeli military officials who helped cover upprocurement fraud.</LP><TEXT>   General Electric, which supplied jet engines for Israelifighter planes, was one U.S. company cited in Israeli pressaccounts of the allegations, according to the WashingtonPost. The reports identified Herbert B. Steindler, a GEexecutive, as having been the manager in charge of companysales to the Israeli air force.   &quot;GE has become aware of the investigation by the Israeligovernment,&quot; said a GE spokesman. &quot;The company has initiatedits own internal investigation concerning the purchase orderssaid to be involved in the Israeli investigation.&quot; He said GEhas informed the U.S. government of its actions, adding that&quot;GE is cooperating fully with the U.S. governmentinvestigation.&quot;   The spokesman declined to comment on when GE learned ofthe allegations or when it began its own investigation.</TEXT></DOC>